  <p class="text-white/55 leading-relaxed mb-4">Each tenant maps tiers to specific models via their routing category configuration. A category's <code class="bg-white/5 px-1.5 py-0.5 rounded text-[#38bdf8] text-sm font-mono">defaultModel</code> field overrides the tier default.</p>

  <h3 class="text-lg font-semibold text-white/90 mt-6 mb-2">Token Thresholds</h3>
  <p class="text-white/55 leading-relaxed mb-4">Token count boundaries used for tier selection when the classifier is bypassed or as a baseline signal:</p>
  <div class="overflow-x-auto mb-6">
    <table class="w-full border-collapse">
      <thead>
        <tr>
          <th class="bg-white/5 text-left text-white/70 px-4 py-2 text-sm">Tier</th>
          <th class="bg-white/5 text-left text-white/70 px-4 py-2 text-sm">Token Threshold</th>
        </tr>
      </thead>
      <tbody>
        <tr>
          <td class="border-t border-white/10 px-4 py-2 text-white/50 text-sm"><code class="bg-white/5 px-1.5 py-0.5 rounded text-[#38bdf8] text-sm font-mono">micro</code></td>
          <td class="border-t border-white/10 px-4 py-2 text-white/50 text-sm">&lt; 150 tokens</td>
        </tr>
        <tr>
          <td class="border-t border-white/10 px-4 py-2 text-white/50 text-sm"><code class="bg-white/5 px-1.5 py-0.5 rounded text-[#38bdf8] text-sm font-mono">minimal</code></td>
          <td class="border-t border-white/10 px-4 py-2 text-white/50 text-sm">&lt; 500 tokens</td>
        </tr>
        <tr>
          <td class="border-t border-white/10 px-4 py-2 text-white/50 text-sm"><code class="bg-white/5 px-1.5 py-0.5 rounded text-[#38bdf8] text-sm font-mono">low</code></td>
          <td class="border-t border-white/10 px-4 py-2 text-white/50 text-sm">&lt; 2,000 tokens</td>
        </tr>
        <tr>
          <td class="border-t border-white/10 px-4 py-2 text-white/50 text-sm"><code class="bg-white/5 px-1.5 py-0.5 rounded text-[#38bdf8] text-sm font-mono">medium</code></td>
          <td class="border-t border-white/10 px-4 py-2 text-white/50 text-sm">&lt; 15,000 tokens</td>
        </tr>
        <tr>
          <td class="border-t border-white/10 px-4 py-2 text-white/50 text-sm"><code class="bg-white/5 px-1.5 py-0.5 rounded text-[#38bdf8] text-sm font-mono">alwaysHigh</code></td>
          <td class="border-t border-white/10 px-4 py-2 text-white/50 text-sm">&ge; 50,000 tokens (forces high tier regardless of other signals)</td>
        </tr>
      </tbody>
    </table>
  </div>

  <h2 class="text-2xl font-semibold text-white mt-10 mb-4">Signal Extraction</h2>
  <p class="text-white/55 leading-relaxed mb-4">Before the LLM classifier is invoked, structural signals are extracted from the raw request. These signals are cheap (microseconds, no API calls) and often sufficient to make a routing decision.</p>

  <h3 class="text-lg font-semibold text-white/90 mt-6 mb-2">Token Count</h3>
  <p class="text-white/55 leading-relaxed mb-4">The total token count of all messages (system + history + current user message) is the strongest single signal for tier selection.</p>
  <pre class="bg-[#0d0d14] border border-white/10 rounded-lg p-4 overflow-x-auto text-sm text-white/70 mb-6 font-mono"><code>&lt; 150 tokens    ->  micro tier candidate           
150-500         ->  minimal tier candidate
500-2 000       ->  low tier candidate
2 000-15 000    ->  medium tier candidate
&gt; 15 000        ->  high tier candidate (long_context_processing)
&gt; 50 000        ->  always high tier (alwaysHigh), regardless of other signals</code></pre>
  <p class="text-white/55 leading-relaxed mb-4">Token count is estimated offline using a character-based heuristic (~3.5 chars/token, code-aware) — no tokenizer dependency.</p>

  <h3 class="text-lg font-semibold text-white/90 mt-6 mb-2">System Prompt Role Detection</h3>
  <p class="text-white/55 leading-relaxed mb-4">The system prompt defines the "mode" of the entire session and overrides most other signals.</p>
  <pre class="bg-[#0d0d14] border border-white/10 rounded-lg p-4 overflow-x-auto text-sm text-white/70 mb-6 font-mono"><code>"You are a senior security auditor..."     ->  code_security_review, high tier
"You are a customer support agent..."      ->  customer_support, low tier
"You are a legal compliance advisor..."    ->  legal_analysis, domain=legal, medium tier min
"You are a data scientist..."              ->  data_analysis, medium tier</code></pre>
  <p class="text-white/55 leading-relaxed mb-4">If the system prompt matches a known role pattern, the category is set directly and the LLM classifier is skipped.</p>

  <h3 class="text-lg font-semibold text-white/90 mt-6 mb-2">Keyword Rules (configurable)</h3>
  <p class="text-white/55 leading-relaxed mb-4">Keyword rules scan the full message content for domain-specific terms. Each rule specifies:</p>
  <ul class="list-disc ml-6 text-white/55 space-y-1 mb-4">
    <li><strong class="text-white/80">keywords</strong> — list of strings to search for (case-insensitive)</li>
    <li><strong class="text-white/80">match</strong> — <code class="bg-white/5 px-1.5 py-0.5 rounded text-[#38bdf8] text-sm font-mono">any</code> (one keyword sufficient) or <code class="bg-white/5 px-1.5 py-0.5 rounded text-[#38bdf8] text-sm font-mono">all</code> (all must appear)</li>
    <li><strong class="text-white/80">minMatches</strong> — minimum number of keyword hits required</li>
    <li><strong class="text-white/80">effect</strong> — what happens: override category, set a minimum tier, set a domain flag</li>
  </ul>
  <p class="text-white/55 leading-relaxed mb-4">Built-in examples:</p>
  <pre class="bg-[#0d0d14] border border-white/10 rounded-lg p-4 overflow-x-auto text-sm text-white/70 mb-6 font-mono"><code>Security Escalation:
  keywords: [private key, jwt, secret, vulnerability, CVE, exploit, crypto]
  match: any, minMatches: 2
  effect: category=code_security_review, tierMin=high

Legal Domain:
  keywords: [GDPR, NDA, liability, compliance, contract, Article]
  match: any, minMatches: 1
  effect: tierMin=medium, domain=legal

Medical Domain:
  keywords: [diagnosis, ICD, treatment, medication, symptoms, clinical]
  match: any, minMatches: 1
  effect: tierMin=medium, domain=medical</code></pre>
  <p class="text-white/55 leading-relaxed mb-4">Keyword rules are stored in the database and fully editable via the admin UI — no deployment required.</p>

  <h3 class="text-lg font-semibold text-white/90 mt-6 mb-2">Code Language Detection</h3>
  <p class="text-white/55 leading-relaxed mb-4">The content is scanned for language-specific patterns to enable capability-based model selection:</p>
  <pre class="bg-[#0d0d14] border border-white/10 rounded-lg p-4 overflow-x-auto text-sm text-white/70 mb-6 font-mono"><code>Patterns detected:  .sol, pragma solidity, contract   ->  blockchain
                    def , import , .py                ->  python
                    SELECT, JOIN, CREATE TABLE         ->  sql
                    BEGIN CERTIFICATE, -----BEGIN     ->  crypto/certificates
                    func , go mod, :=                 ->  go</code></pre>
  <p class="text-white/55 leading-relaxed mb-4">A detected language influences which model is selected within the target tier — for example, routing Python code tasks to <code class="bg-white/5 px-1.5 py-0.5 rounded text-[#38bdf8] text-sm font-mono">codestral</code> or <code class="bg-white/5 px-1.5 py-0.5 rounded text-[#38bdf8] text-sm font-mono">deepseek-coder-v2</code> instead of a general-purpose model of the same tier.</p>

  <h3 class="text-lg font-semibold text-white/90 mt-6 mb-2">Content Type</h3>
  <pre class="bg-[#0d0d14] border border-white/10 rounded-lg p-4 overflow-x-auto text-sm text-white/70 mb-6 font-mono"><code>images in messages          ->  vision model required (see Vision Upgrade override)
tool_calls in messages      ->  function-calling capable model required
structured output schema    ->  JSON-mode capable model preferred
streaming: false            ->  no streaming constraint — any model eligible</code></pre>

  <h3 class="text-lg font-semibold text-white/90 mt-6 mb-2">Conversation Turn Count</h3>
  <p class="text-white/55 leading-relaxed mb-4">Longer conversations carry accumulated context and often involve follow-up complexity:</p>
  <pre class="bg-[#0d0d14] border border-white/10 rounded-lg p-4 overflow-x-auto text-sm text-white/70 mb-6 font-mono"><code>turns 1-3   ->  no effect
turns 4-7   ->  +1 tier upgrade (configurable)
turns 8+    ->  +1 tier upgrade, long_context_processing flag</code></pre>
  <p class="text-white/55 leading-relaxed mb-4">Turn-based upgrades are suppressed for categories that are inherently stateless (e.g. <code class="bg-white/5 px-1.5 py-0.5 rounded text-[#38bdf8] text-sm font-mono">summarization_short</code>, <code class="bg-white/5 px-1.5 py-0.5 rounded text-[#38bdf8] text-sm font-mono">translation</code>).</p>

  <h3 class="text-lg font-semibold text-white/90 mt-6 mb-2">FIM / Autocomplete Detection
   
  </h3>
  <p class="text-white/55 leading-relaxed mb-4">IDE autocomplete and Fill-in-the-Middle (FIM) requests are detected before any other routing step. These requests are latency-sensitive, produce short output, and require zero reasoning — they are routed to the <code class="bg-white/5 px-1.5 py-0.5 rounded text-[#38bdf8] text-sm font-mono">low</code> tier (coder-optimised models like qwen3-coder) without calling the LLM classifier.</p>
  <p class="text-white/55 leading-relaxed mb-4">Detection uses two signal sources:</p>
  <ul class="list-disc ml-6 text-white/55 space-y-1 mb-4">
    <li><strong class="text-white/80">System prompt / first user message patterns</strong> — keywords like "hole filler", "fill in the middle", "FIM", "code completion", "autocomplete", "fill the hole", "inline completion", <code class="bg-white/5 px-1.5 py-0.5 rounded text-[#38bdf8] text-sm font-mono">&#123;&#123;HOLE&#125;&#125;</code>. Both the system prompt and the first user message are checked ( — fixes OpenCode-style clients that embed the instruction in the first user turn)</li>
    <li><strong class="text-white/80">FIM content tokens</strong> — special tokens embedded in the message content by IDE clients: <code class="bg-white/5 px-1.5 py-0.5 rounded text-[#38bdf8] text-sm font-mono">&lt;fim_prefix&gt;</code>, <code class="bg-white/5 px-1.5 py-0.5 rounded text-[#38bdf8] text-sm font-mono">&lt;fim_suffix&gt;</code>, <code class="bg-white/5 px-1.5 py-0.5 rounded text-[#38bdf8] text-sm font-mono">[PREFIX]</code>, <code class="bg-white/5 px-1.5 py-0.5 rounded text-[#38bdf8] text-sm font-mono">[SUFFIX]</code>, <code class="bg-white/5 px-1.5 py-0.5 rounded text-[#38bdf8] text-sm font-mono">&lt;PRE&gt;</code>, <code class="bg-white/5 px-1.5 py-0.5 rounded text-[#38bdf8] text-sm font-mono">&lt;SUF&gt;</code>, <code class="bg-white/5 px-1.5 py-0.5 rounded text-[#38bdf8] text-sm font-mono">&#123;&#123;HOLE&#125;&#125;</code>, <code class="bg-white/5 px-1.5 py-0.5 rounded text-[#38bdf8] text-sm font-mono">&lt;CURSOR&gt;</code>, etc.</li>
  </ul>
  <p class="text-white/55 leading-relaxed mb-4">Supported token formats include StarCoder, DeepSeek, CodeLlama, Mistral/Codestral, SantaCoder, Continue.dev HoleFiller, and generic FIM markers. When detected, the request is pre-routed to category <code class="bg-white/5 px-1.5 py-0.5 rounded text-[#38bdf8] text-sm font-mono">coding_autocomplete</code> with confidence 0.99 and source <code class="bg-white/5 px-1.5 py-0.5 rounded text-[#38bdf8] text-sm font-mono">fim_detection</code>. This bypasses both the override rules and the LLM classifier entirely.</p>
  <pre class="bg-[#0d0d14] border border-white/10 rounded-lg p-4 overflow-x-auto text-sm text-white/70 mb-6 font-mono"><code>FIM request detected → coding_autocomplete, low tier, conf=0.99
                       Skip rules, skip classifier
                       ~0ms routing overhead</code></pre>

  <h3 class="text-lg font-semibold text-white/90 mt-6 mb-2">Tool-Agent Detection
   
  </h3>
  <p class="text-white/55 leading-relaxed mb-4">Requests from AI coding agents (Claude Code, OpenCode, Cursor, Windsurf) are detected by their system prompt. Tool-agent detection produces a <strong class="text-white/80">hint</strong> (confidence 0.55, below classifier threshold) rather than a final pre-route. This means the LLM classifier still runs for tool-agent requests, properly differentiating between simple tool calls (<code class="bg-white/5 px-1.5 py-0.5 rounded text-[#38bdf8] text-sm font-mono">tool_use</code>, medium tier) and complex multi-step coding (<code class="bg-white/5 px-1.5 py-0.5 rounded text-[#38bdf8] text-sm font-mono">swe_agentic</code>, high tier). The default "Coding Agent / SWE" system prompt role sets <code class="bg-white/5 px-1.5 py-0.5 rounded text-[#38bdf8] text-sm font-mono">tierMin: medium</code> as a floor — the classifier escalates complex tasks to higher tiers automatically.</p>
  <p class="text-white/55 leading-relaxed mb-4">Detected patterns include: "file search specialist", "expert software engineer", "agentic coding", "thoroughly navigating and exploring codebases", "in agent mode", <code class="bg-white/5 px-1.5 py-0.5 rounded text-[#38bdf8] text-sm font-mono">&lt;tool_use_instructions&gt;</code> XML blocks, and tool codec syntax. The hint is used as fallback only if no rule-set match produces a stronger result.</p>

  <h2 class="text-2xl font-semibold text-white mt-10 mb-4">Tier Cap
   
  </h2>
  <p class="text-white/55 leading-relaxed mb-4">When a client explicitly requests a specific model but auto-routing is enabled via <code class="bg-white/5 px-1.5 py-0.5 rounded text-[#38bdf8] text-sm font-mono">model=auto</code>, the routing result is <strong class="text-white/80">capped at the requested model's tier</strong>. If routing would select a more expensive tier, the original model is used instead. This prevents unexpected cost escalation.</p>
  <p class="text-white/55 leading-relaxed mb-4"><strong class="text-white/80">Exception</strong>: the tier cap does <strong class="text-white/80">not</strong> apply when <code class="bg-white/5 px-1.5 py-0.5 rounded text-[#38bdf8] text-sm font-mono">forceAutoRoute</code> is enabled on the tenant. In that case, the admin explicitly wants the router to pick the best model regardless of what the client requested.</p>
  <pre class="bg-[#0d0d14] border border-white/10 rounded-lg p-4 overflow-x-auto text-sm text-white/70 mb-6 font-mono"><code>Client requests:   claude-sonnet-4-6 (high tier)
Routing decides:   claude-opus-4-6 (ultra tier)
Tier cap applies:  ultra > high → use original model
overrideApplied:   tier_cap:claude-sonnet-4-6</code></pre>

  <h2 class="text-2xl font-semibold text-white mt-10 mb-4">Override Rules</h2>
  <p class="text-white/55 leading-relaxed mb-4">After signal extraction, a set of override rules adjusts the routing result. Overrides are applied in order; the first matching override wins (or they can stack — configurable).</p>
  <div class="overflow-x-auto mb-6">
    <table class="w-full border-collapse">
      <thead>
        <tr>
          <th class="bg-white/5 text-left text-white/70 px-4 py-2 text-sm">Override</th>
          <th class="bg-white/5 text-left text-white/70 px-4 py-2 text-sm">Condition</th>
          <th class="bg-white/5 text-left text-white/70 px-4 py-2 text-sm">Effect</th>
        </tr>
      </thead>
      <tbody>
        <tr><td class="border-t border-white/10 px-4 py-2 text-white/50 text-sm"><strong class="text-white/80">Vision Upgrade</strong></td><td class="border-t border-white/10 px-4 py-2 text-white/50 text-sm">Images present, category doesn't require vision</td><td class="border-t border-white/10 px-4 py-2 text-white/50 text-sm">Upgrade tier by 1</td></tr>
        <tr><td class="border-t border-white/10 px-4 py-2 text-white/50 text-sm"><strong class="text-white/80">Tool Call Upgrade</strong></td><td class="border-t border-white/10 px-4 py-2 text-white/50 text-sm">Request contains tool/function definitions</td><td class="border-t border-white/10 px-4 py-2 text-white/50 text-sm">Force minimum tier (configurable, default: <code class="bg-white/5 px-1.5 py-0.5 rounded text-[#38bdf8] text-sm font-mono">medium</code>)</td></tr>
        <tr><td class="border-t border-white/10 px-4 py-2 text-white/50 text-sm"><strong class="text-white/80">Security Escalation</strong></td><td class="border-t border-white/10 px-4 py-2 text-white/50 text-sm">Security keywords >= threshold</td><td class="border-t border-white/10 px-4 py-2 text-white/50 text-sm">Force <code class="bg-white/5 px-1.5 py-0.5 rounded text-[#38bdf8] text-sm font-mono">code_security_review</code>, <code class="bg-white/5 px-1.5 py-0.5 rounded text-[#38bdf8] text-sm font-mono">high</code> tier</td></tr>
        <tr><td class="border-t border-white/10 px-4 py-2 text-white/50 text-sm"><strong class="text-white/80">Domain Gate</strong></td><td class="border-t border-white/10 px-4 py-2 text-white/50 text-sm">Domain = legal / medical / finance</td><td class="border-t border-white/10 px-4 py-2 text-white/50 text-sm">Tier minimum <code class="bg-white/5 px-1.5 py-0.5 rounded text-[#38bdf8] text-sm font-mono">medium</code></td></tr>
        <tr><td class="border-t border-white/10 px-4 py-2 text-white/50 text-sm"><strong class="text-white/80">Confidence Fallback</strong></td><td class="border-t border-white/10 px-4 py-2 text-white/50 text-sm">Classifier confidence &lt; threshold (default 0.65)</td><td class="border-t border-white/10 px-4 py-2 text-white/50 text-sm">Force <code class="bg-white/5 px-1.5 py-0.5 rounded text-[#38bdf8] text-sm font-mono">medium</code> tier</td></tr>
        <tr><td class="border-t border-white/10 px-4 py-2 text-white/50 text-sm"><strong class="text-white/80">Conversation Turn Upgrade</strong></td><td class="border-t border-white/10 px-4 py-2 text-white/50 text-sm">Turns >= 4</td><td class="border-t border-white/10 px-4 py-2 text-white/50 text-sm">+1 tier</td></tr>
        <tr><td class="border-t border-white/10 px-4 py-2 text-white/50 text-sm"><strong class="text-white/80">Frustration Upgrade</strong></td><td class="border-t border-white/10 px-4 py-2 text-white/50 text-sm">User frustration signal detected</td><td class="border-t border-white/10 px-4 py-2 text-white/50 text-sm">+1 tier</td></tr>
        <tr><td class="border-t border-white/10 px-4 py-2 text-white/50 text-sm"><strong class="text-white/80">Output Length Upgrade</strong></td><td class="border-t border-white/10 px-4 py-2 text-white/50 text-sm">Estimated output = long, tier = minimal</td><td class="border-t border-white/10 px-4 py-2 text-white/50 text-sm">Upgrade to <code class="bg-white/5 px-1.5 py-0.5 rounded text-[#38bdf8] text-sm font-mono">low</code></td></tr>
        <tr><td class="border-t border-white/10 px-4 py-2 text-white/50 text-sm"><strong class="text-white/80">Budget Cap</strong></td><td class="border-t border-white/10 px-4 py-2 text-white/50 text-sm">Tenant daily spend >= alert threshold</td><td class="border-t border-white/10 px-4 py-2 text-white/50 text-sm">Downgrade to configured max tier</td></tr>
      </tbody>
    </table>
  </div>
  <p class="text-white/55 leading-relaxed mb-4">All overrides are individually toggleable and threshold-adjustable per tenant via the admin UI.</p>

  <h2 class="text-2xl font-semibold text-white mt-10 mb-4">LLM Classifier</h2>
  <p class="text-white/55 leading-relaxed mb-4">When pre-routing signals produce a confidence below the configured threshold (default: 0.65), the LLM classifier is called. It receives a structured summary of the request — not the full content — and returns a JSON routing decision.</p>

  <h3 class="text-lg font-semibold text-white/90 mt-6 mb-2">What the classifier receives</h3>
  <pre class="bg-[#0d0d14] border border-white/10 rounded-lg p-4 overflow-x-auto text-sm text-white/70 mb-6 font-mono"><code>[System]
You are a precise model router. Classify the request into one of:
- code_generation [low] — Examples: write function, implement class, ...
- data_analysis [medium] — Examples: analyze dataset, find patterns, ...
- reasoning_formal [high] — Examples: prove theorem, formal logic, ...
... (all 45 categories with tier and examples)

Reply with ONLY valid JSON, no markdown:
&#123;"category":"...","confidence":0-1,"complexity":"simple|medium|complex",
 "has_image":bool,"language":"en|de|other","estimated_output_length":"short|medium|long",
 "domain":"general|legal|medical|finance|tech|science","conversation_turn":int,
 "user_frustration_signal":bool,"cost_tier":"micro|minimal|low|medium|advanced|high|ultra|critical","reasoning":"..."&#125;

[User]
[System]: You are a coding assistant...  (truncated to 500 chars)
[user]: Analyse this repository and identify security vulnerabilities
[CONTEXT_SIGNALS: tokens=82000, languages=[python,yaml], security_keywords=3, turns=1]</code></pre>
  <p class="text-white/55 leading-relaxed mb-4">Note that context signals are injected as metadata — the classifier never sees the full file contents. This keeps the classifier call small and fast regardless of how large the actual payload is.</p>

  <h3 class="text-lg font-semibold text-white/90 mt-6 mb-2">Classifier Context Limit Handling</h3>
  <p class="text-white/55 leading-relaxed mb-4">Different classifier models have vastly different context windows:</p>
  <div class="overflow-x-auto mb-6">
    <table class="w-full border-collapse">
      <thead>
        <tr>
          <th class="bg-white/5 text-left text-white/70 px-4 py-2 text-sm">Model</th>
          <th class="bg-white/5 text-left text-white/70 px-4 py-2 text-sm">Context window</th>
          <th class="bg-white/5 text-left text-white/70 px-4 py-2 text-sm">Recommended strategy</th>
        </tr>
      </thead>
      <tbody>
        <tr><td class="border-t border-white/10 px-4 py-2 text-white/50 text-sm"><code class="bg-white/5 px-1.5 py-0.5 rounded text-[#38bdf8] text-sm font-mono">gpt-4o-mini</code></td><td class="border-t border-white/10 px-4 py-2 text-white/50 text-sm">128,000 tokens</td><td class="border-t border-white/10 px-4 py-2 text-white/50 text-sm"><code class="bg-white/5 px-1.5 py-0.5 rounded text-[#38bdf8] text-sm font-mono">truncate</code></td></tr>
        <tr><td class="border-t border-white/10 px-4 py-2 text-white/50 text-sm"><code class="bg-white/5 px-1.5 py-0.5 rounded text-[#38bdf8] text-sm font-mono">claude-haiku-4-5</code></td><td class="border-t border-white/10 px-4 py-2 text-white/50 text-sm">200,000 tokens</td><td class="border-t border-white/10 px-4 py-2 text-white/50 text-sm"><code class="bg-white/5 px-1.5 py-0.5 rounded text-[#38bdf8] text-sm font-mono">truncate</code></td></tr>
        <tr><td class="border-t border-white/10 px-4 py-2 text-white/50 text-sm"><code class="bg-white/5 px-1.5 py-0.5 rounded text-[#38bdf8] text-sm font-mono">llama-3.1-8b</code></td><td class="border-t border-white/10 px-4 py-2 text-white/50 text-sm">8,192 tokens</td><td class="border-t border-white/10 px-4 py-2 text-white/50 text-sm"><code class="bg-white/5 px-1.5 py-0.5 rounded text-[#38bdf8] text-sm font-mono">metadata_only</code></td></tr>
        <tr><td class="border-t border-white/10 px-4 py-2 text-white/50 text-sm"><code class="bg-white/5 px-1.5 py-0.5 rounded text-[#38bdf8] text-sm font-mono">gemini-flash-2.0</code></td><td class="border-t border-white/10 px-4 py-2 text-white/50 text-sm">1,000,000 tokens</td><td class="border-t border-white/10 px-4 py-2 text-white/50 text-sm"><code class="bg-white/5 px-1.5 py-0.5 rounded text-[#38bdf8] text-sm font-mono">truncate</code></td></tr>
        <tr><td class="border-t border-white/10 px-4 py-2 text-white/50 text-sm"><code class="bg-white/5 px-1.5 py-0.5 rounded text-[#38bdf8] text-sm font-mono">phi-4</code></td><td class="border-t border-white/10 px-4 py-2 text-white/50 text-sm">16,384 tokens</td><td class="border-t border-white/10 px-4 py-2 text-white/50 text-sm"><code class="bg-white/5 px-1.5 py-0.5 rounded text-[#38bdf8] text-sm font-mono">summary</code></td></tr>
      </tbody>
    </table>
  </div>
  <p class="text-white/55 leading-relaxed mb-4">Three strategies are supported:</p>
  <p class="text-white/55 leading-relaxed mb-4"><strong class="text-white/80"><code class="bg-white/5 px-1.5 py-0.5 rounded text-[#38bdf8] text-sm font-mono">metadata_only</code></strong> — the classifier never sees message content, only extracted metadata. Safest for small-context models (&lt; 16k tokens). Lowest classification quality for ambiguous prompts.</p>
  <p class="text-white/55 leading-relaxed mb-4"><strong class="text-white/80"><code class="bg-white/5 px-1.5 py-0.5 rounded text-[#38bdf8] text-sm font-mono">truncate</code></strong> — the last user message and a truncated system prompt are included up to <code class="bg-white/5 px-1.5 py-0.5 rounded text-[#38bdf8] text-sm font-mono">contextLimit x 0.6</code> tokens (leaving headroom for the category list and output). Best trade-off for most models.</p>
  <p class="text-white/55 leading-relaxed mb-4"><strong class="text-white/80"><code class="bg-white/5 px-1.5 py-0.5 rounded text-[#38bdf8] text-sm font-mono">summary</code></strong> — a cheap, fast model first generates a 200-token summary of the full context, then the classifier receives that summary. Highest quality for long inputs, but adds one extra API hop.</p>
  <p class="text-white/55 leading-relaxed mb-4">The strategy and context limit are configured per tenant in the Routing Config UI.</p>

  <h2 class="text-2xl font-semibold text-white mt-10 mb-4">Smart Classifier Fallback
   
  </h2>
  <p class="text-white/55 leading-relaxed mb-4">When all configured classifiers fail (rate limits, timeouts, network errors, invalid JSON response), the router no longer throws an error and falls back to the tenant's default model (which is often the most expensive). Instead, it selects a tier based on the request's token count:</p>
  <pre class="bg-[#0d0d14] border border-white/10 rounded-lg p-4 overflow-x-auto text-sm text-white/70 mb-6 font-mono"><code>&le; 150 tokens     →  micro           
&le; 500 tokens     →  minimal
&le; 2 000 tokens   →  low
&le; 15 000 tokens  →  medium
&le; 50 000 tokens  →  high
&gt; 50 000 tokens  →  ultra</code></pre>
  <p class="text-white/55 leading-relaxed mb-4">This prevents cost spikes when the classifier is temporarily unavailable. The fallback is logged as <code class="bg-white/5 px-1.5 py-0.5 rounded text-[#38bdf8] text-sm font-mono">overrideApplied: classifier_fallback</code> with <code class="bg-white/5 px-1.5 py-0.5 rounded text-[#38bdf8] text-sm font-mono">reason: token_fallback (...)</code> for full observability.</p>

  <h2 class="text-2xl font-semibold text-white mt-10 mb-4">Session Context-Fill Routing
   
  </h2>
  <p class="text-white/55 leading-relaxed mb-4">After each successful request, the gateway caches the <strong class="text-white/80">context fill percentage</strong> (<code class="bg-white/5 px-1.5 py-0.5 rounded text-[#38bdf8] text-sm font-mono">inputTokens / contextWindow</code>) per session (30-minute TTL, in-memory). On the next request in the same session, if the previous fill was &ge; 75%, the router automatically steps up one tier so the request lands on a model with sufficient headroom before a context overflow occurs.</p>
  <pre class="bg-[#0d0d14] border border-white/10 rounded-lg p-4 overflow-x-auto text-sm text-white/70 mb-6 font-mono"><code>Previous request: 150k tokens / 200k context = 75% fill
Next request:     low tier → medium tier (proactive upgrade)
                  overrideApplied: session_context_upgrade(75%)</code></pre>
  <p class="text-white/55 leading-relaxed mb-4">The threshold is configurable per tenant via <code class="bg-white/5 px-1.5 py-0.5 rounded text-[#38bdf8] text-sm font-mono">routing.sessionFillUpgradeThreshold</code> (default: 0.75). The previous fill percentage is stored as <code class="bg-white/5 px-1.5 py-0.5 rounded text-[#38bdf8] text-sm font-mono">prevSessionFillPct</code> in routing signals for post-hoc analysis.</p>
  <p class="text-white/55 leading-relaxed mb-4">Session fill state survives pod restarts — on a cache miss the gateway recovers fill state from the last successful <code class="bg-white/5 px-1.5 py-0.5 rounded text-[#38bdf8] text-sm font-mono">RequestLog</code> entry for the session. The pre-flight context check also uses a 10% safety margin: when estimated fill &ge; 90% of the context window, the router proactively switches to a larger model before overflow occurs.</p>

  <h3 class="text-lg font-semibold text-white/90 mt-6 mb-2">Message Truncation as Last Resort
   
  </h3>
  <p class="text-white/55 leading-relaxed mb-4">When context overflows and no larger model is available (session has grown to the platform limit), the gateway truncates old conversation turns rather than returning an error. Strategy: keep the system prompt and most recent turns, drop oldest turns until the payload fits within 85% of the context window, inject a synthetic system note so the model knows history was cut. This applies to both proactive pre-flight detection and reactive overflow paths.</p>

  <h2 class="text-2xl font-semibold text-white mt-10 mb-4">Cost Mode &amp; Tier Boost
   
  </h2>
  <p class="text-white/55 leading-relaxed mb-4">After all classification and override rules have been applied, two final adjustments can shift the resolved tier:</p>
  <p class="text-white/55 leading-relaxed mb-4"><strong class="text-white/80">Cost Mode</strong> — configured per rule set. Three options:</p>
  <ul class="list-disc pl-6 space-y-1 text-white/55 text-sm mb-4">
    <li><strong class="text-white/80">Economy (−1 tier)</strong> — step down one tier to save cost</li>
    <li><strong class="text-white/80">Balanced</strong> — no adjustment (default)</li>
    <li><strong class="text-white/80">Quality (+1 tier)</strong> — step up one tier for better output quality</li>
  </ul>
  <p class="text-white/55 leading-relaxed mb-4"><strong class="text-white/80">Tier Boost</strong> — an explicit offset (−2 to +2) that stacks with cost mode. For example, quality (+1) combined with tier boost (+1) yields a total shift of +2 tiers. Configured per rule set in the Routing Config UI.</p>
  <pre class="bg-[#0d0d14] border border-white/10 rounded-lg p-4 overflow-x-auto text-sm text-white/70 mb-6 font-mono"><code>Classifier result:  coding_medium → medium tier
Cost mode (quality): medium → advanced (+1)
Tier boost (+1):     advanced → high (+1)
Final tier:          high
overrideApplied:     cost_quality+tier_boost:+1</code></pre>

  <h2 class="text-2xl font-semibold text-white mt-10 mb-4">Test Route (Dry-Run)
   
  </h2>
  <p class="text-white/55 leading-relaxed mb-4">The <strong class="text-white/80">Test Route</strong> tab in Routing Config lets you dry-run any prompt through the full routing pipeline and see a step-by-step trace of every decision point:</p>
  <ol class="list-decimal pl-6 space-y-1 text-white/55 text-sm mb-4">
    <li>Signal extraction (tokens, images, tool calls, domains, languages)</li>
    <li>FIM / tool-agent fast-path detection</li>
    <li>Rule-set pre-routing (which keyword rules and system prompt roles matched)</li>
    <li>Classifier decision (use or skip, and why)</li>
    <li>Classifier output (category, tier, confidence, recommended model, reasoning)</li>
    <li>Post-classifier tier enforcement (rule-set floor applied?)</li>
    <li>Tenant override rules (which triggered, what changed)</li>
    <li>Cost mode adjustment</li>
    <li>Tier boost adjustment</li>
    <li>Model selection (method, final model, provider)</li>
  </ol>
  <p class="text-white/55 leading-relaxed mb-4">Each step shows whether it changed the result (green) or was a no-op (gray), with detailed JSON data. Optionally enable <strong class="text-white/80">"Call real classifier"</strong> to make an actual LLM call for production-identical results (costs tokens).</p>

  <h2 class="text-2xl font-semibold text-white mt-10 mb-4">Synthetic Tests
    <span class="ml-2 inline-block text-[10px] font-semibold px-1.5 py-0.5 rounded bg-purple-500/15 text-purple-400 border border-purple-500/25 align-middle">AI</span>
   
  </h2>
  <p class="text-white/55 leading-relaxed mb-4">Synthetic Tests let you automatically evaluate your routing configuration quality using AI-generated test suites:</p>
  <ol class="list-decimal pl-6 space-y-1 text-white/55 text-sm mb-4">
    <li><strong class="text-white/80">Create a test suite</strong> — name it and optionally scope to a specific category</li>
    <li><strong class="text-white/80">Generate test prompts</strong> — choose any available model to generate realistic prompts with expected categories and tiers</li>
    <li><strong class="text-white/80">Run the suite</strong> — execute all test prompts against the current routing config (pre-routing only, no LLM calls, no cost)</li>
    <li><strong class="text-white/80">AI Evaluate</strong> — choose any available model to analyze the results and get a routing quality score (0–100) plus actionable suggestions</li>
  </ol>
  <p class="text-white/55 leading-relaxed mb-4">The evaluation provides two types of recommendations: <strong class="text-white/80">quality suggestions</strong> (how to improve routing accuracy) and <strong class="text-white/80">cost suggestions</strong> (how to reduce spending). Test runs are persisted and can be compared over time to track routing improvements.</p>

